    <title>Combined summary - Statechain implementations</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T00:25:20.825165+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-March/017723.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Statechains is a proposed layer 2 scaling solution for Bitcoin that aims to enable the change of ownership of an individual position in a discreet log contract (DLC) without an on-chain transaction and without requiring cooperation from the counterparty. The protocol involves a key generation process and a transfer protocol that can be repeated to transfer ownership to new owners. However, modifications are being considered to enhance the protocol, such as using a decrementing nLocktime for backup transactions and replacing the multisig output with a single P2(W)PKH output.Email threads on the bitcoin-dev mailing list discuss modifications to the statechains concept and enhancements needed, such as atomic swapping multiple UTXOs and binary decomposition of value in lots. Additionally, the article discusses the mechanism to replace old first stage transactions with new ones that have 0 relative locktime.The SE role in statechains requires a significant amount of computational power, making brute force attacks difficult to combat effectively. Therefore, minimizing trust is crucial while running the SE role. This can be achieved by incorporating modifications such as running the role inside an AWS oracle or hardware isolated processor like SGX. The proposal recommends utilizing an AWS oracle or SGX to run the SE role securely and efficiently.Various enhancements have been proposed to make the system more efficient and secure, including atomic swaps, key exchange, and Lightning integration. The email chain also discussed potential attacks on the protocol, and solutions were proposed to address these concerns. Modifications to the statechains protocol were discussed, including using a decrementing nLocktime for backup transactions and replacing the 2-of-2 multisig output with a single P2(W)PKH output shared between the SE and the current owner.There are concerns about the possibility of untraceably scamming its users, which could be mitigated by adding a new user key to the protocol for traceability/provability. Tom Trevethan is leading the implementation of the Statechains concept, with particular interest in using the protocol to enable the change of ownership of an individual position in an active discreet log contract (DLC) without an on-chain transaction and without requiring the cooperation of the counterparty. Ruben Somsen and Christian Decker discuss potential modifications to statechains, including using a kickoff transaction with a secondary output that can be spent by anyone to fee bump the transaction with Child Pays For Parent (CPFP), and two-party ECDSA to redistribute keys without requiring an on-chain move to be committed.Trevethan's patent application for "Secure off-chain blockchain transactions" has been rejected on the grounds of prior art. Overall, statechains have potential benefits for the Bitcoin ecosystem, but modifications and enhancements are needed to ensure their security and workability. Feedback on the proposed modifications is welcomed, indicating that the proposal is open to refining and improving. In conclusion, modifying the statechains protocol to mitigate trust issues and enhance security can significantly improve the reliability and effectiveness of the SE role.</summary>
